title: For Trade:  Stag Arms Model 3 Package
postcontent:
I've decided to get out of the AR game and looking to unload everything I have. I've put roughly 1000 rounds through my rifle with extensive cleaning after every range trip. The package will include the following:

Stag Arms Model 3 Flattop 1/7 twist
11 30rnd Black windowless P-mags
1 60rnd Surefire mag
1 30rnd Metal mag
1 42rnd Metal mag
Vortex Strikefire Optic w/1x magnifier(http://www.vortexoptics.com/category/red_dots)
890 rounds of 5.56 (Most of the p-mags are loaded with green tip XM855 with the last few rounds being tracers, the surefire is loaded with green tip xm855 with tracers as well)
Magpul flip-up sights
Magpul pistol grip w/storage
Front foregrip with battery storage and the side panels come off for a pressure switch for a light
Extended charging handle

Now what I'm looking for in trade:

I want an AK-47. Mag for Mag, round for round. I'm looking for a Bulgarian imported by Arsenal but I might entertain others. Wood furniture is preferred but I'm flexible.

Trade Value for my package $1600 (Cost me almost $2000(pre-panic prices) for everything)
I also have the original grip, the different backs for the magpul grip, the original charging handle. Original case.

I might entertain other trades. But an AK is what I'm really looking for, what you can't make up in ammo or mags I will take cash instead. Keep in mind the value of the AR is $890 brand new. I may entertain multiple firearm trades as well. If you've got a H&K USPc in 9mm and an AK-47 we can definitely make a deal. Below is the price breakdown.



-Stag Arms Model 3 - MSRP $890, Lowest price online I could find was $781 before shipping and transfer costs. So I’ll put the value at $750, which is definitely less than what I paid for it.
-11 P-mags - I’ve seen the price on these drop back down to as low as $12 without a dust cover. Most of my mags have the dust cover so I’ll put the value at $13 a piece for $143 total
-The two metal mags I’ll put them at $5 a piece so $10 total.
-The Vortex sight retails for just below $200 online I paid $180 for it not even two weeks ago.
-The ammo is around 350 rounds of steel core Federal 5.56 the rest is mostly on the higher end of FMJ with a small amount of cheaper surplus. Even though some ammo is almost a dollar a round that price is way too high in my opinion so mine with the higher end ammo in it. I think .59 a round is more appropriate. So for 890 rounds the price rounds out to $529. So I’ll just put that at $400.
-The Surefire 60 round magazine(which has functioned flawlessly) originally ran for around $50 or so before the panic so I’ll just keep it at that.
-The magpul sights cost me around $60 for the pair, so we’ll just say $50 for those.
-The magpul pistol grip I believe cost me around $35, it stores three rounds and has three different back straps. So I’ll just say $20 for it.
-Front foregrip is worth around $20.
-Extended charging handle is $10.

So after all the used prices are put together it comes too $1633. Some of the mags, ammo, and parts I bought while prices were inflated so I spent closer to $2000 for all of it. But in the price breakdown I didn't list the prices I actually paid for some of the stuff(Like a dollar a round ammo or $30 P-mags) So the trade value is less than what you would of spent to buy everything brand new without inflated prices.

The last of the 3rd generation GLOCKS, that could be considered a 3.5 generation pistol, were the RTF2s, the first of which, the model 22 was released in November of 2009. The RTF2s have a modified grip texture that uses lots of little raised dots set in a grid pattern. It is called the Ruff Texture Frame 2, being that it is the second version of GLOCKS ruff textured grips. The only other change made were the slide serrations being changed from the normal straight design to a curved gill serration. The gill serrations were produced on the slides of .40S&W (22 announced January of 2009 & 23 announced November of 2009) and 9mm (17 announced May of 2009 & 19 announced November of 2009), although, later productions of GLOCK 17, 19, 22 & 23 are produced with normal straight slide serrations.
